{"title":"BMW’s big electric car push: Selling 2 million new EVs by 2025","link":"https://arstechnica.com/?p=1750277","date":1615993487000,"content":"<div id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"><div><header><h4>big nose energy —</h4><h2 itemprop=\"description\">The iX arrives next year, but expect \"mid $80s\" pricing for the big BEV.</h2></header><div itemprop=\"articleBody\"><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90407622_highRes-800x533.jpg\" alt=\"A BMW iX being built at its factory\"><figcaption><p><a href=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90407622_highRes.jpg\" data-height=\"2000\" data-width=\"3000\">Enlarge</a> <span>/</span> A BMW iX rolls down the production line at Dingolfing, Germany.</p><p>BMW</p></figcaption></figure><p>With annual report season in full swing,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://report.bmwgroup.com/home/intro/\">it was BMW's turn</a>&nbsp;on Wednesday to take the microphone and tell us about its electric vehicle plans for the next few years. The German automaker was an early leader in terms of electrification, producing innovative cars under <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/cars/2017/12/bmw-i-is-how-the-ultimate-driving-machine-is-adapting-to-the-future/\">the \"i\" subbrand</a> and <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/cars/2016/05/one-in-seven-new-bmws-sold-in-the-us-is-a-electric-vehicle/\">selling a lot of plug-in hybrids to boot</a>. But it fell behind rivals in the development of longer-range battery EVs, which is&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/foreign/2019/07/08/bmw-ceo-felled-slow-transition-electric/39657027/\">one reason</a> why then-CEO Harald Krugër stepped down in 2019 just weeks after <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/cars/2019/06/bmw-speeds-up-plans-to-electrify-25-new-models-now-due-by-2023/\">announcing plans to amp up the electrification effort</a>.</p><p>He was succeeded by current CEO Oliver Zipse, who is now pushing the accelerator pedal. BMW's plug-in sales were strong in 2020 despite the obvious challenges, increasing sales to 193,000 units. For 2021, Zipse wants this number to grow by 75 percent. If the company succeeds, it will have sold 1 million plug-in vehicles since 2013. BMW says it will have 13 BEVs on sale in 2023, from compact cars to the biggest, most luxurious cars to wear the blue-and-white propeller. And by the end of 2025, the plan is for BMW to have delivered a total of 2 million plug-ins to customers.</p><h2>This is the new BMW i4</h2><div><ul><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416003_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416003_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416003_highRes-980x654.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416003_highRes-1440x960.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750280\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750280\"><span></span><p>The new BMW i4 electric vehicle.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416000_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416000_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416000_highRes-980x654.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416000_highRes-1440x960.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750283\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750283\"><span></span><p>At last year's not-Geneva auto show, BMW showed off the Concept i4. Now it's the production car's turn.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416005_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416005_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416005_highRes-980x654.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416005_highRes-1440x960.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750278\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750278\"><span></span><p>BMW says this is a Gran Coupé. Technically, coupe means cut, and the lower rear roofline compared to a normal sedan just about fits the definition. Even though everyone understands the term to mean you've cut a pair of doors out...</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416004_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416004_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416004_highRes-980x654.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416004_highRes-1440x960.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750279\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750279\"><span></span><p>No tailpipes here.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416002_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416002_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416002_highRes-980x654.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90416002_highRes-1440x960.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750281\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750281\"><span></span><p>At least one version of i4 should have a 300-mile range.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li></ul></div><p>BMW also showed off a little of its next production BEV, a four-door sedan called the i4. It adheres closely to <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/cars/2020/03/who-did-the-future-electric-sedan-best-bmw-or-hyundai/\">the Concept i4 we saw this time last year</a>, although it's a little less concept-y, obviously. BMW said it will release full details about the i4 in the coming weeks, but it did say the car \"will enter the market during the course of 2021,\" three months ahead of schedule, and that one version should have an EPA range of 300 miles (590 km under WLTP).</p><h2>iX SUV deliveries start in 2022</h2><div><ul><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90407676_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90407676_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90407676_highRes-980x551.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90407676_highRes-1440x810.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750292\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750292\"><span></span><p>This is a cutaway of BMW's next flagship, the iX SUV.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414543_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414543_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414543_highRes-980x437.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414543_highRes-1440x643.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750287\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750287\"><span></span><p>Two BMW iXs.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414553_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414553_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414553_highRes-980x734.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414553_highRes-1440x1079.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750286\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750286\"><span></span><p>It's not particularly elegant, but I don't think the intended audience cares.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414556_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414556_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414556_highRes-980x734.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414556_highRes-1440x1079.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750285\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750285\"><span></span><p>And I'd definitely rather have one of these than an X7.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414557_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414557_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414557_highRes-980x732.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414557_highRes-1440x1075.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750284\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750284\"><span></span><p>This angle hides the grille.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414528_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414528_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414528_highRes-980x653.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414528_highRes-1440x960.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750291\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750291\"><span></span><p>Originally I thought this was a charging port but it might be something else.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90405592_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90405592_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90405592_highRes-980x653.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90405592_highRes-1440x960.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750294\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750294\"><span></span><p>The production iX's interior is a lot more restrained than the show car (for understandable reasons), but with the right mix of trim materials, it still has some of the same flavor.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90407440_highRes_the-first-ever-bmw-i-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90407440_highRes_the-first-ever-bmw-i.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90407440_highRes_the-first-ever-bmw-i-980x653.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90407440_highRes_the-first-ever-bmw-i-1440x960.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750300\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750300\"><span></span><p>I think it loses some of the \"boutique hotel\" effect when everything is wrapped in red leather.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414535_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414535_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414535_highRes-980x654.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414535_highRes-1440x960.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750290\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750290\"><span></span><p>Luxury brand flagships always have some interesting options, like this coat hanger attachment.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li><li data-thumb=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414536_highRes-150x150.jpg\" data-src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414536_highRes.jpg\" data-responsive=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414536_highRes-980x654.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/P90414536_highRes-1440x960.jpg 2560\" data-sub-html=\"#caption-1750289\"><figure><figcaption id=\"caption-1750289\"><span></span><p>Or you could have a small tray table and drink holder.</p><p><span></span> BMW</p></figcaption></figure></li></ul></div><p>We did get more info on BMW's next BEV, the iX SUV. We first saw this one<a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/cars/2018/09/we-got-our-first-good-look-at-bmws-new-electric-inext-on-sale-in-2021/\">—inside a Boeing 777F cargo plane, no less</a>—as the iNext concept in 2019. Then, <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/cars/2020/11/the-ix-is-bmws-new-flagship-electric-vehicle/\">last November, BMW took the wraps off the production version</a>. When it reaches US showrooms in early 2022, the car will mark the end of one era and the beginning of another. For decades, BMW's flagship has been the big, powerful 7 Series sedan; now it will be a big, powerful electric SUV.</p><p>It's more sustainable to build, both in terms of the raw materials it uses (less cobalt, fewer rare-earths, more recycled plastics and fabrics) and the electricity required to turn that all into an SUV. And BMW said that its new fifth-generation drive unit is much better packaged, with 30 percent greater power density than previous systems. (The company also quoted the drive units as being 93 percent efficient.)</p><p>The battery pack uses prismatic cells, and the range-topping iX xDrive50 will pack more than 100 kWh under the cabin, sufficient for an EPA range of 300 miles (600 km WLTP). And BMW reiterated the fact that it will fast-charge at up to 200 kW, charging from 10 to 80 percent in 40 minutes. This strongly implies that the iX uses an 800 V electrical architecture, as current 400 V DC fast chargers top out at 150 kW, but BMW's press kit doesn't go that in-depth.</p><p>Flagships aren't cheap, however. US pricing hasn't been finalized yet, but BMW said that it expects the iX to start \"in the mid $80s.\"</p></div></div></div>","author":"Jonathan M. Gitlin","siteTitle":"Ars Technica","siteHash":"5b0ddf6e8923e49262a7894cfd77962733e43fbcc565a103b48373820b310636","entryHash":"730cfb609e76ed9acceefb4068cda6f68ec35931d986884b696fa9cca44fdcbe","category":"Tech"}